            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Do you mean “secondary agent” in a particular domain (software/multi‑agent system, legal power of attorney, security/2FA, healthcare, customer support, etc.)? If so, tell me which and I’ll give a focused answer. Meanwhile, here’s a concise general overview of what a secondary agent can do:\n\n- Backup / failover: take over when the primary agent fails or is unavailable.  \n- Support / assist: handle lower‑priority or auxiliary tasks so the primary can focus on core work.  \n- Monitoring and alerting: watch system health, log events, and raise alerts.  \n- Limited delegated authority: perform actions within defined permissions or only under certain conditions (common in power of attorney or administrative roles).  \n- Escalation and triage: accept incidents, do initial diagnostics, and escalate complex cases to the primary.  \n- Data collection and aggregation: gather telemetry, summarize results, and prepare reports.  \n- Testing/simulation: act as a simulated counterpart to validate workflows or train the primary.  \n- Security checks and auditing: perform secondary verification, audit trails, or second‑factor approvals.  \n- Recovery and remediation: perform rollback, cleanup, or recovery tasks after errors.\n\nExample contexts:\n- Software agent: a secondary microservice might queue tasks, retry failed jobs, and alert the ops team if the primary service is down.  \n- Power of attorney: a secondary agent acts on behalf of the principal only if the primary is unwilling/unavailable, and usually with limited powers.\n\nWhich context do you have in mind or what specific capabilities are you considering for the secondary agent?",
